"_____________________________________________________________"
"Bern uses a Odin-like syntax for loops."
"This means that the only word for loops is \"for\""
"And the way you type it changes how the loop behaves."
"_____________________________________________________________\n"

"[1. Repeat For]"
"The \"Repeat For\" loop repeats an action a specified number of times:"
"for 3 do"
"    \"Hello, Loops!\""
"end"

"\nResult:"
for 3 do
    "Hello, Loops!"
end

"\n_____________________________________________________________\n"


"[2. Conditional For]"
"The \"Conditional For\" loop repeats an action until the conditional is false:"
"counter = 2"
"for counter > 0 do"
"    \"Hello, Loops!\""
"    counter = counter - 1"
"end"

"\nResult:"
counter = 2
for (counter > 0) do
    "Hello, Loops!"
    counter = counter - 1
end

"\n_____________________________________________________________\n"
"[3. Infinite For]"
"To do a Infinite Loop, use for true like this:"
"for true do"
"   \"Hello!\""
"end"

-- Commented to run normally.
